{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f53d2c0c-0872-459f-b2e4-e6916593829e","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA` has been on a deprecation path in .NET for several releases:\n\n1. **`SYSLIB0028`** — `DSA.Create()` and the DSA family were marked `[Obsolete]` starting in .NET 7.\n2. **macOS specifically** — Apple's native crypto framework (`Security.framework`) has **never** supported DSA. Older .NET versions fell back to an OpenSSL-based managed shim on macOS.\n3. **In .NET 11** — Microsoft completed the removal of that fallback. `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and will eventually on all platforms).\n\nLinux/Windows still work for now because they have OS-level DSA support (OpenSSL / CNG), but this is borrowed time — DSA is fully obsolete.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Use [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography) for DSA verification.** It's a pure managed implementation with no OS crypto dependency:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyLegacyDsaSignature(\n    byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] message, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory\n        .CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA-1withDSA\");\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n**Long-term**, migrate those legacy signatures to **ECDSA** or **EdDSA** — DSA is cryptographically weak and deprecated everywhere, not just .NET.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9448e39-578c-4a79-9319-4319cd29e56c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this.\n\nThis is a known issue in the .NET ecosystem. Let me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically, DSA support on macOS has been a known pain point because macOS's native crypto library (Apple's CryptoKit/Security framework) doesn't support DSA. In earlier .NET versions, the implementation used OpenSSL on macOS for DSA operations.\n\n\nThe real problem is that on Apple platforms, `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because the underlying Security framework simply doesn't have DSA support built in. While Microsoft marked DSA as obsolete starting in .NET 7 and continued deprecating legacy cryptographic algorithms through .NET 9, the core issue is the platform limitation itself rather than a version-specific breaking change. the fallback was removed entirely. The solutions would involve either switching to a third-party library like BouncyCastle that still supports DSA, bundling OpenSSL explicitly, or migrating to a modern algorithm like RSA or ECDSA if the signatures can be re-signed. This is a known compatibility issue where DSA was marked obsolete starting around .NET 7, and on macOS specifically, Apple's Security framework never had DSA support to begin with.","outputTokens":1362,"requestId":"7044:2A85DF:8FEB56:A626C7:69FBEE99"},"id":"03b05c95-4b42-4918-bdbd-df5042acb20b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:45:31.976Z","parentId":"9b4b44f8-f160-4028-9c35-b34b93bc2f9b"}
